{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dfcc0a62-7a0e-415b-b34c-fd54d2d8b2c0","content":"Yes, these are known **MSTest v4 behavioral breaking changes** that compile cleanly but fail at runtime:\n\n## 1. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it no longer carries a test name (it's `null`). This is by design since class init runs before any specific test.\n\n**Fix:** Don't access `TestContext.TestName` in `ClassInitialize`. If you need it for logging, use a fallback:\n\n```csharp\nvar name = context.TestName ?? \"(class-level)\";\n```\n\nOr move that logic into `[TestInitialize]` where the instance `TestContext` has the test name.\n\n## 2. Discovery errors\n\nYour `[ClassInitialize]` method signature uses the **legacy form**. MSTest v4 requires you to explicitly declare the `InheritanceBehavior` parameter or opt in via attribute. The old single-parameter overload can cause discovery failures in v4.\n\n**Fix:** Update the signature:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize(InheritanceBehavior.None)]\npublic static void ClassSetup(TestContext context)\n```\n\n---\n\nWant me to apply both fixes to your file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9b605899-dbb8-4a5b-9d5d-a9229be9d6b9","outputTokens":301,"requestId":"981B:B2C21:1418E40:192EC1B:69FFF96B"},"id":"6044c5ba-3f8e-4e3a-8930-cd152af8f93a","timestamp":"2026-05-10T03:20:20.613Z","parentId":"c6184197-f7d9-473e-9ecd-e34840dfcf69"}
